  <content>
    <title>Market Research: TAM/SAM/SOM Triangulation</title>

    <summary>Three nested market size calculations (TAM = total addressable, SAM = serviceable available, SOM = realistically obtainable) computed via three independent methods (top-down from reports, bottom-up from customer counts, competitor-based from revenue proxies) and triangulated. Lock the ICP definition before any number is fetched. Round aggressively — two significant figures max. Express SOM as a customer count first, dollars second.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Entrepreneurs either overestimate markets ("It's a billion dollar opportunity!") or underestimate them because there is no practical method to size markets for solo products. The root failure is using top-down numbers without grounding: a Statista headline TAM without a bottom-up customer count is a guess dressed as data. Running three methods and triangulating forces the agent to reconcile contradictions before the estimate enters a deliverable.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-spec phase: sanity check whether a niche clears a revenue floor (e.g. SOM > $1M ARR in 3 years).</item>
        <item>Pitch decks, investor memos, grant applications requiring a numerical market frame.</item>
        <item>Pricing or positioning decisions where segment economics matter (SAM × ARPU sets the envelope).</item>
        <item>Comparing two adjacent niches before committing to MVP scope.</item>
        <item>Annual roadmap review as market segment shifts (new geography, new tier, post-funding).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Hobby projects, internal tools, free OSS — sizing adds zero signal.</item>
        <item>Replacement for actual customer interviews — TAM/SAM/SOM is not problem validation.</item>
        <item>Already-shipping products with real ARR — extrapolate from cohorts, not market reports.</item>
        <item>Two-sided marketplaces in pre-launch — supply/demand dynamics dominate raw market size.</item>
        <item>Deep-tech with a 10-year horizon — the market category may not exist yet.</item>
        <item>Regulated markets pre-license (medical, fintech) — addressable share depends on regulator decisions.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="tam-definition">
      <title>TAM: Total Addressable Market</title>
      <p>Total revenue if the product captured 100% of the market. Formula: total potential customers × average revenue per customer. Use case: show the ceiling; not realistic but shows opportunity size.</p>
      <example type="good" title="TAM calculation example">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
All small businesses globally: 400M
Average software spend: $1,000/year
TAM = 400M × $1,000 = $400B
        ]]></code>
        <note>TAM is the ceiling, not the target. Investors know this; never present TAM as achievable.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="sam-definition">
      <title>SAM: Serviceable Available Market</title>
      <p>Portion of TAM that can actually be served given constraints (geography, language, industry, company size, tech stack). Formula: TAM × segment percentage.</p>
      <example type="good" title="SAM calculation with justified constraints">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
TAM: $400B small business software
Constraints: US-based, e-commerce, 1-50 employees
SAM = $400B × 2% = $8B
        ]]></code>
        <note>Each constraint must be justified with data or a sourced estimate. Stacking four unsourced percentages creates compounding error.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="som-definition">
      <title>SOM: Serviceable Obtainable Market</title>
      <p>Realistic market share capturable in 3-5 years. Formula: SAM × realistic market share. Realistic share: Year 1 = 0.1-0.5%, Year 3 = 1-3%, Year 5 = 3-10%.</p>
      <example type="good" title="SOM expressed as customer count first, dollars second">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
SAM: $8B
Year 3 target: 0.5% share
SOM = $8B × 0.5% = $40M
Express as: 4,000 customers × $10,000/year = $40M
        ]]></code>
        <note>Always express SOM as customer count first, dollars second. "4,000 customers" is testable; "$40M" is not.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="method-1-top-down">
      <title>Method 1: Top-Down from Industry Reports</title>
      <p>Start with industry reports, narrow down: Industry Size → Segment → Geography → SOM. Pros: uses established data. Cons: can be disconnected from reality if segment assumptions are unsourced.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="method-2-bottom-up">
      <title>Method 2: Bottom-Up from Customer Counts</title>
      <p>Start with customers, multiply up: # potential customers × conversion rate × price = revenue. Pros: grounded in reality. Cons: may underestimate opportunity; requires accurate customer counts.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For B2B markets, use government establishment data (US Census BDS, Eurostat) as the top-down customer count anchor — it is free and primary.</statement>
        <rationale>LinkedIn Sales Navigator counts are inaccessible for pipelines; Statista customer counts are paywalled. Government data is free, primary, and reliable for establishment counts by NAICS/NACE code.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="method-3-competitor-based">
      <title>Method 3: Competitor-Based Market Estimation</title>
      <p>Use competitor revenues to estimate total market: sum named competitor revenues + extrapolate long tail (typically 1.5× of named players). Sources: Crunchbase funding, SimilarWeb traffic estimates, LinkedIn employee count × $200K (B2B SaaS only, 20+ employees).</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LinkedIn employee count × $200K rule used for companies under 20 people or for services businesses.</description>
        <reason>The rule undercounts services and overcounts seed-stage SaaS. It is only valid for growth-stage B2B SaaS companies where sales-to-headcount ratios are established.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="triangulation-rule">
      <title>Triangulation and Divergence Flagging</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run all three methods independently before triangulation. Never run bottom-up after reviewing top-down results — anchoring bias inflates the bottom-up estimate.</statement>
        <rationale>If the agent sees a $10B top-down TAM before computing the bottom-up, it will unconsciously reverse-engineer to produce a consistent number. Independence requires sequential blind computation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>If methods diverge by more than 2x, do NOT average — report the range and flag the divergence. Investigate the outlier method before reconciling.</statement>
        <rationale>Averaging incompatible methods produces false precision. A 2x spread signals that one method's assumptions are wrong; averaging hides the problem and misleads investors.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="icp-lock-rule">
      <title>ICP Lock Rule (Critical)</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Lock the ICP definition in one sentence and wait for explicit confirmation before fetching any number. "All SMBs" is not an ICP.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents computing TAM/SAM/SOM without a locked ICP will scope to different customer segments across the three methods, making triangulation impossible and producing numbers that cannot be compared.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-pipeline">
      <title>Agentic Market Sizing Pipeline (7 Steps)</title>
      <list>
        <item>Step 1 — ICP lock: restate ICP in one sentence, await confirmation.</item>
        <item>Step 2 — Top-down fetch: WebSearch for "{industry} market size {year}", capture top 3 sources, prefer government/Statista/Gartner; archive each via Wayback.</item>
        <item>Step 3 — Bottom-up build: count target companies via Census/Eurostat/Apollo, multiply by realistic ARPU.</item>
        <item>Step 4 — Competitor sweep: pull Crunchbase + SimilarWeb for top 5 competitors, sum + extrapolate long tail (1.5× named players).</item>
        <item>Step 5 — Triangulate: run tam-triangulate.sh; write median to report only when spread is 2× or less.</item>
        <item>Step 6 — Confidence tagging: tag every cell H/M/L based on source primacy and recency (12 months or less = H).</item>
        <item>Step 7 — Validation pass: secondary agent re-reads report and returns a delta list.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <title>Sizing and Validation Prompt Patterns</title>
      <example type="good" title="Sizing and validation prompts">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Sizing prompt:
You are a market sizer. Compute TAM, SAM, SOM for: <niche>.
Constraints: <geo, segment, ICP>. Horizon: 3 years.
Run THREE methods (top-down, bottom-up, competitor) in parallel.
For every number cite the source URL + retrieval date.
If methods diverge >2x, do NOT average — return both and flag.
Output: markdown matching the Market Sizing Report template.

Validation prompt:
Validate this sizing: <numbers + assumptions>.
Check: (1) does TAM cite a primary source? (2) is SAM constraint stack independent?
(3) is SOM share within Year-N guidelines? Return a delta list, not a rewrite.
        ]]></code>
        <note>Sizing and validation are separate agent calls with separate prompts. The validator reads the sizing output; it does not regenerate.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <title>Best Practices for Market Sizing</title>
      <list>
        <item>Lock the ICP definition in one sentence before any number is computed; "all SMBs" is not an ICP.</item>
        <item>Always run bottom-up second, after top-down — it forces the agent to reconcile, not to anchor.</item>
        <item>Cite source + retrieval date on every line; archive paywalled pages via Wayback before quoting.</item>
        <item>Round aggressively: $8.3B is fake precision, $8B is honest. Two significant figures max for TAM/SAM.</item>
        <item>Express SOM as a customer count first, dollars second: "1,000 customers × $50/mo" beats "$600K".</item>
        <item>Keep an assumptions ledger at the bottom of the report — every multiplier on its own row, swappable.</item>
        <item>Re-run the sizing every 6 months; diff the assumptions, not the headline number.</item>
        <item>For B2B, use government establishment data (Census/Eurostat) as the top-down anchor — it is free and primary.</item>
        <item>Cross-check competitor revenue with two independent signals (e.g. Crunchbase ARR + SimilarWeb traffic) before trusting a number.</item>
        <item>Tag every multiplier as Hard (sourced) or Soft (estimate); refuse to publish if Soft multipliers compound more than 3 deep.</item>
        <item>Capture the report as a git commit under .aidocs/product_docs/ so future sizings can git diff against the baseline.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <title>CLI Tools and Services for Market Sizing</title>
      <list>
        <item>gh (GitHub CLI): Pull competitor repos, stars, contributor counts as a proxy for traction.</item>
        <item>crunchbase-api (REST): Funding, headcount, founded-year for competitor sizing.</item>
        <item>similarweb-api: Traffic, engagement, top countries — feeds bottom-up reach math.</item>
        <item>linkedin-api (unofficial Python lib): ICP count via Sales Nav search; respect ToS, prefer official.</item>
        <item>census-bureau-api (US, free): Establishment counts by NAICS for ground-truth top-down.</item>
        <item>eurostat-api (EU, free): Same for EU establishments by NACE.</item>
        <item>statista (no public API): Paid; scrape via authenticated session, cite report ID.</item>
        <item>wayback-machine (waybackpack): Pin a market-report URL to a retrieval date for reproducibility.</item>
        <item>pandoc + csvkit: Convert pulled tables into the report template.</item>
        <item>claude (Anthropic CLI): Run the agent prompts in batch.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Services and apps: Statista (paid market reports, partial — HTML scrape, no open API), Gartner / Forrester (paid analyst reports, no — PDFs behind enterprise paywall), IBISWorld (industry reports, partial — login scrape), Crunchbase (funding/competitor DB, yes — REST API, key required), PitchBook (private market data, partial — enterprise API), SimilarWeb (traffic estimates, yes — REST API, paid), Semrush / Ahrefs (SEO traffic, yes — REST API), LinkedIn Sales Navigator (ICP counting, hostile — ToS blocks scraping), Google Trends (demand signal, yes — pytrends), US Census BDS, Eurostat, OECD (government stats, yes — free APIs), Apollo.io / Clearbit (B2B contact DB, yes — REST API), Product Hunt (launch traction, yes — GraphQL API), G2 / Capterra (software reviews, partial — scrape).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <title>AI Agent Gotchas and Anti-Patterns</title>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinate market-size numbers fluently; they require a URL for every figure.</description>
        <reason>Reject any line without a source URL. LLMs generate plausible-sounding numbers (e.g. "$4.2B by 2027") that have no factual basis. The URL is the only enforcement mechanism.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Confirmation bias: if the user hints at a target market size, the agent will reverse-engineer to that number.</description>
        <reason>Pre-commit the methodology and share the ICP definition before revealing the hypothesis. The agent must compute the number before seeing the founder's expectation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Currency drift: agents mix USD, EUR, GBP within one report.</description>
        <reason>Normalize to USD with a dated FX rate in the report preamble. Require the agent to convert all figures before synthesizing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Confusing GMV with revenue: marketplaces report GMV; SaaS reports ARR. Adding them is invalid.</description>
        <reason>The agent must identify the revenue metric type for each competitor before including it in the competitor-based sizing. Mixed metrics produce incorrect TAM estimates.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Stale training data: the model "knows" 2023 market sizes and uses them unless forced to fetch.</description>
        <reason>Force a fresh web fetch for any post-2024 market number. Add an explicit instruction: "Do not use training data for market size figures; always fetch from a cited source."</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Multiplication of fractions: 0.6 × 0.5 × 0.5 × 0.01 generates false precision.</description>
        <reason>Round each multiplier to one significant figure before multiplying.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ignoring growth: a static $5B TAM today may be $9B at a 12% CAGR in 5 years.</description>
        <reason>SOM horizon must match TAM horizon. If sizing for 3-year SOM, use 3-year-forward TAM figures.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>"LinkedIn employee count × $200K" rule undercounts services and overcounts seed-stage SaaS.</description>
        <reason>Disable for any company under 20 people. Use this heuristic only for growth-stage B2B SaaS companies with established sales-to-headcount ratios.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <title>Limitations and Known Failure Modes</title>
      <list>
        <item>Garbage-in: agents pull a Statista headline number from a paywalled snippet and treat it as ground truth.</item>
        <item>Compounding error: TAM × 2% × 50% × 0.5% creates four-decimal precision from four guesses.</item>
        <item>Stale data: most "market size" reports cited online are 2-3 years old; CAGR projections diverge fast.</item>
        <item>Survivor bias in competitor-based sizing: only public/funded competitors are visible; long tail is invisible.</item>
        <item>"LinkedIn × $200K/employee" is a rule of thumb that breaks for high-margin SaaS and low-margin services.</item>
        <item>SOM is the most-faked number in startup decks; LLMs tend to anchor on whatever the user hints at.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/market-sizing-report.md" purpose="Full market sizing report structure with all required sections, assumptions ledger, and confidence tagging."/>
      <template path="templates/quick-market-check.md" purpose="15-minute rough market check template for initial scoping."/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/tam-triangulate.sh" purpose="Flags divergence across three sizing methods; exits 1 if spread > 2x."/>
    </scripts>

